NOTES: Dr. Mike Brown will speak at Astronomy Club on February 15 at 10:30 PST in Centra.  Dr. Brown is a professor of planetary astronomy at theCalifornia Institute of Technology.  He is sometimes called “the Pluto Killer” for his involvement in downgrading Pluto’s status as a planet  This talk is open to all OHS students, so join us to hear this brilliant speaker!Email Ayla Besemer at abesemer@stanford.edu if you would like to be enrolled in the event on Centra.

A Completely Naturalistic Account of the Mind: What It Would Require…and Why It Might Be Impossible to Achieve    Joshua Beattie, Core Instructor    February 15, 2013 – 1 p.m.Summary:Nobody can deny that there have been incredible advances in our scientific understanding of the brain and the way it underwrites certain mental capacities. But questions remain about the big picture. In short, can we give a broad and generalized account of the mind that is fully naturalistic? Or do certain features of the mind resist such treatment? I will briefly discuss a major approach to this naturalistic project and one big obstacle it faces: the seemingly ineliminable role of rational connections – e.g. that a set of beliefs makes sense of or justifies a particular action – in determining which cognitive states are which.
This is a discussion, led by Dr. Keating, about the Feb. 8th speaker.
